159. nevis is a reading not absolutely certain in this place, and it is possible that Plautus wrote the common non vis. See Ritschl, Opusc. 11 249. But in support of our reading we may quote the analogous passage, Poen. v 2, 119, at te moneri num nevis? See, how- ever, 8150 Most. 336.

161. Megadorus contemptu- ously calls a wife of somewhat maturer years anns, to express that she is nearly old enough to deserve this title. The epi· thets senex and anus are, how- ever, not to be taken as expres- sive of a very old age, as they are sometimes applied to persons of about 45 to 50 years. E. g. Amphitruo is styled se- nex in the comedy bearing his name v 1, 20, and Π 2, 12, though he seems a newly- married man in the prime of his years.
